      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">Neodymium is a silvery-yellowish metal belonging to the lanthanide series. Neodymium is reactive; it reacts with oxygen from air to form neodymium(III) oxide - N</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">d</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">2</text>
      </subsup>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">O</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">, and reacts with sulphur, the halogens, hydrogen and nitrogen. At elevated temperatures neodymium reacts with water, displacing hydrogen and producing neodymium(III) hydroxide - Nd(OH</text>
      <subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">)</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="13" fc="0" fa="1" charset="238"></text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">3</text>
      </subsup>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238">.  Neodymium was first obtained by the Austrian chemist Carl Auer von Welsbach in 1885. Its name is derived from the Greek words </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="238">neos</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> - new and </text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fs="i" fa="1" charset="238">didymos</text>
      <text fn="Arial" fh="15" fc="16777215" fa="1" charset="238"> - didymium (a mixture of rare-earth elements, once thought to be a single element).</text>
   </par>
